    let merchId = document.getElementById('merchId').value;
    return merchId;
}
```

In the modified version:

1. We changed the way we retrieve the content from the element to `.value` for input fields.
2. Ensure that there is an element with the ID 'merchId' in the HTML document.

You can now use this function to retrieve the value of an input field with the ID 'merchId'. If the element is not an input field, you can revert to using `.innerText` if the content is text-based or other appropriate properties based on the type of the element.

To use the `getMerchId()` JavaScript function within an HTML form, you can call the function when the form is submitted or on another specific event. You can then display or use the returned value from the function in your form.

Here's an example of how you can incorporate the `getMerchId()` function into an HTML form:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
<head>
    <title>Get Merch ID from Form</title>
</head>
<body>
    <form id="myForm">
        <label for="merchId">Merch ID:</label>
        <input type="text" id="merchId">
        <button type="button" onclick="displayMerchId()">Display Merch ID</button>
    </form>

    <script>
        function getMerchId() {
            // Get the value from the input field with the id 'merchId'
            let merchId = document.getElementById('merchId').value;
